{"id":"2212.01949","submitter":"Ofir Gorodetsky","authors":"Ofir Gorodetsky","title":"Friable integers and de Bruijn's approximation $\\Lambda$","comments":"26 pages, previously part of arXiv:2211.08973v1. Fixed missing breaks\n  in arXiv abstract, submitted, comments still welcome","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NT","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  This paper is concerned with the relationship of $y$-friable (i.e.\n$y$-smooth) integers and de Bruijn's approximation $\\Lambda(x,y)$. Under the\nRiemann Hypothesis (RH), Saias proved that the count of $y$-friable integers up\nto $x$, $\\Psi(x,y)$, is asymptotic to $\\Lambda(x,y)$ when $y \\ge (\\log\nx)^{2+\\varepsilon}$. We extend the range to $y \\ge (\\log x)^{3/2+\\varepsilon}$\nby introducing a correction factor that takes into account the contributions of\nzeta zeros and prime powers.\n  We use this correction term to discover a lower order term in the asymptotics\nof $\\Psi(x,y)/\\Lambda(x,y)$. The term relates directly to the error term in the\nprime number theorem, and implies that large positive (resp. negative) values\nof $\\sum_{n \\le y} \\Lambda(n)-y$ lead to large positive (resp. negative) values\nof $\\Psi(x,y)-\\Lambda(x,y)$, and vice versa. This holds for $y$ as small as\n$(\\log x)^{2+\\varepsilon}$. This is the first result demonstrating sign changes\nfor friable numbers.\n  Under the Linear Independence hypothesis, we show a Chebyshev's bias in\n$\\Psi(x,y)-\\Lambda(x,y)$ for $y$ as small as $(\\log x)^{2+\\varepsilon}$.\n  As a consequence of our methods, we obtain (under RH) another verification of\na conjecture of Hildebrand, recently resolved by the author, on the\nrelationship of $\\Psi(x,y)$ and the Dickman function for $y=(\\log\nx)^{2-\\varepsilon}$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 4 Dec 2022 23:04:35 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 7 Dec 2022 15:08:18 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-08"}
