{"id":"2212.02001","submitter":"Fang Tian","authors":"Fang Tian, Yiting Yang","title":"A note on the random triadic process","comments":"17 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO math.PR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Let $\\mathbb{H}_3(n,p)$ be a random $3$-uniform hypergraph on\n$n\\rightarrow\\infty$ vertices where each triple is an edge randomly and\nindependently with probability $p$. The random triadic process starts with the\nstar $K_{1,n-1}$ on the same vertex set and iteratively adds an edge $xy$ if\nthere is a vertex $z$ such that $xz$ and $yz$ are already in the graph and\n$xzy\\in \\mathbb{H}_3(n,p)$. Kor\\'{a}ndi et al. proved a sharp threshold\nprobability for the propagation of the process, that is, if $p= cn^{ - \\frac\n12}$ for some positive constant $c$, with high probability, the triadic process\nreaches the complete graph when $c> \\frac 12$ and stops at $O(n^{\\frac 32})$\nedges when $c< \\frac 12$. In this note, we generalize their approach to\nconsider the final size of the process when $p$ lies in the range of\n$p\\geqslant c_0 n^{-1}\\log^\\alpha n$ and $p=o( n^{- \\frac 12})$ for some\npositive constants $c_0$ and $\\alpha>1$. We track each variable with the exact\nexpected trajectory and better error term in the first phase and finally show\nthat, with high probability, the process stops at $O(c(n)n^{2-s})$ edges when\n$p$ is expressed in the form of $p= c(n)n^{-s}$ for any constant $s\\in (0,\n\\frac 12)$. Following our proof, we conjecture that $p=n^{-1}\\log n$ is the\nthreshold for the connectivity of the process.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 5 Dec 2022 03:24:26 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-06"}
{"id":"2212.02002","submitter":"Vikram Krishnamurthy","authors":"Kunal Pattanayak and Shashwat Jain and Vikram Krishnamurthy and Chris\n  Berry","title":"Adaptive ECCM for Mitigating Smart Jammers","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"eess.SP cs.LG","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  This paper considers adaptive radar electronic counter-counter measures\n(ECCM) to mitigate ECM by an adversarial jammer. Our ECCM approach models the\njammer-radar interaction as a Principal Agent Problem (PAP), a popular\neconomics framework for interaction between two entities with an information\nimbalance. In our setup, the radar does not know the jammer's utility. Instead,\nthe radar learns the jammer's utility adaptively over time using inverse\nreinforcement learning. The radar's adaptive ECCM objective is two-fold (1)\nmaximize its utility by solving the PAP, and (2) estimate the jammer's utility\nby observing its response. Our adaptive ECCM scheme uses deep ideas from\nrevealed preference in micro-economics and principal agent problem in contract\ntheory. Our numerical results show that, over time, our adaptive ECCM both\nidentifies and mitigates the jammer's utility.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 5 Dec 2022 03:26:07 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-06"}
{"id":"2212.02003","submitter":"Bao Doan","authors":"Bao Gia Doan, Ehsan Abbasnejad, Javen Qinfeng Shi, Damith C.\n  Ranasinghe","title":"Bayesian Learning with Information Gain Provably Bounds Risk for a\n  Robust Adversarial Defense","comments":"Published at ICML 2022","journal-ref":"Proceedings of the 39th International Conference on Machine\n  Learning, PMLR 162:5309-5323, 2022","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.LG cs.CR cs.CV","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/","abstract":"  We present a new algorithm to learn a deep neural network model robust\nagainst adversarial attacks. Previous algorithms demonstrate an adversarially\ntrained Bayesian Neural Network (BNN) provides improved robustness. We\nrecognize the adversarial learning approach for approximating the multi-modal\nposterior distribution of a Bayesian model can lead to mode collapse;\nconsequently, the model's achievements in robustness and performance are\nsub-optimal. Instead, we first propose preventing mode collapse to better\napproximate the multi-modal posterior distribution. Second, based on the\nintuition that a robust model should ignore perturbations and only consider the\ninformative content of the input, we conceptualize and formulate an information\ngain objective to measure and force the information learned from both benign\nand adversarial training instances to be similar. Importantly. we prove and\ndemonstrate that minimizing the information gain objective allows the\nadversarial risk to approach the conventional empirical risk. We believe our\nefforts provide a step toward a basis for a principled method of adversarially\ntraining BNNs. Our model demonstrate significantly improved robustness--up to\n20%--compared with adversarial training and Adv-BNN under PGD attacks with\n0.035 distortion on both CIFAR-10 and STL-10 datasets.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 5 Dec 2022 03:26:08 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-06"}
