{"id":"2212.02009","submitter":"Jean Helder Marques Ribeiro","authors":"Jean H\\'elder Marques Ribeiro, Chi-An Yeh, Kunihiko Taira","title":"Triglobal resolvent analysis of swept-wing wakes","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Through triglobal resolvent analysis, we reveal the effects of wing tip and\nsweep angle on laminar separated wakes over swept wings. For the present study,\nwe consider wings with semi-aspect ratios from $1$ to $4$, sweep angles from\n$0^\\circ$ to $45^\\circ$, and angles of attack of $20^\\circ$ and $30^\\circ$ at a\nchord-based Reynolds number of $400$ and a Mach number of $0.1$. Using direct\nnumerical simulations, we observe that unswept wings develop vortex shedding\nnear the wing root with a quasi-steady tip vortex. For swept wings, vortex\nshedding is seen near the wing tip for low sweep angles, while the wakes are\nsteady for wings with high sweep angles. To gain further insights into the\nmechanisms of flow unsteadiness, triglobal resolvent analysis is used to\nidentify the optimal spatial input-output mode pairs and the associated gains\nover a range of frequencies. The three-dimensional forcing and response modes\nreveal that harmonic fluctuations are directed towards the root for unswept\nwings and towards the wing tip for swept wings. The overlapping region of the\nforcing-response mode pairs uncovers triglobal resolvent wavemakers associated\nwith self-sustained unsteady wakes of swept wings. Furthermore, we show that\nfor low aspect ratio wings optimal perturbations develop globally over the\nentire wingspan. The present study uncovers physical insights on the effects of\ntip and sweep on the growth of optimal harmonic perturbations and the wake\ndynamics of separated flows over swept wings.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 5 Dec 2022 03:42:35 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-06"}
